25|$|If {{an animal}} is {{diagnosed}} with heartworms, treatment may be indicated. Before the worms can be treated, however, the dog must be evaluated for heart, liver, and kidney function {{to evaluate the}} risks of treatment. Usually, the adult worms are killed with an arsenic-based compound. The currently approved drug in the US, melarsomine, is marketed under the brand name Immiticide. It has a greater efficacy and fewer side effects than previously used drug (<b>thiacetarsamide</b> <b>sodium,</b> sold as Caparsolate), {{which makes it a}} safer alternative for dogs with late-stage infections.|$|E

